#: ../../O/suffix-oid.rst:5
msgid "-oid"
msgstr "-oid"

#: ../../O/suffix-oid.rst:7
msgid "suff\\."
msgstr "接尾辞"

#: ../../O/suffix-oid.rst:9
msgid "[from Greek suffix -oid = in the image of]"
msgstr "[ギリシャ語の接尾辞-oid = 〜の姿をした、から]"

#: ../../O/suffix-oid.rst:12
msgid ""
"Used as in mainstream slang English to indicate a poor imitation, a "
"counterfeit, or some otherwise slightly bogus resemblance. Hackers will "
"happily use it with all sorts of non-Greco/Latin stem words that wouldn't "
"keep company with it in mainstream English. For example, \"He's a nerdoid\" "
"means that he superficially resembles a nerd but can't make the grade; a "
"modemoid might be a 300-baud box (Real Modems run at 28.8 or up); a "
"computeroid might be any :ref:`bitty-box`\\. The word keyboid could be used "
"to describe a :ref:`chiclet-keyboard`\\, but would have to be written; "
"spoken, it would confuse the listener as to the speaker's city of origin."
msgstr ""
"主流の俗語英語でのように、粗悪な模倣、まがいもの、あるいはその他のいくぶんbogusな類似を示すのに使われる。ハッカーは、主流の英語ではこれと連れ立つことのない、ありとあらゆる非ギリシャ・ラテン語語幹の単語にこれを喜んで付ける。たとえば\"He's"
" a "
"nerdoid\"は、彼が表面的にはnerdに似ているが基準に達していないことを意味する。modemoidは300ボーの箱かもしれない(本物のModemは28.8以上で走る)。computeroidはあらゆる\\"
" :ref:`bitty-box`\\ かもしれない。keyboidという単語は\\ :ref:`chiclet-keyboard`\\ "
"を表すのに使えるだろうが、書かなければならない。話すと、聞き手は話者の出身都市を取り違えてしまうだろう。"

#: ../../O/suffix-oid.rst:18
msgid ""
"More specifically, an indicator for ‘resembling an android’ which in the "
"past has been confined to science-fiction fans and hackers. It too has "
"recently (in 1991) started to go mainstream (most notably in the term "
"‘trendoid’ for victims of terminal hipness). This is probably traceable to "
"the popularization of the term :ref:`droid` in *Star Wars* and its sequels. "
"(See also :ref:`windoid`\\.)"
msgstr ""
"より具体的には、‘androidに似ている’ことを示す指標で、過去にはSFファンとハッカーに限られていた。これも最近(1991年に)主流化し始めた(最も顕著なのは、末期的な流行追従者を指す‘trendoid’という用語においてである)。これはおそらく、\\"
" *Star Wars*\\ とその続編における\\ :ref:`droid`\\ という用語の普及に遡れる。(\\ :ref:`windoid`\\ "
"も参照。)"

#: ../../O/suffix-oid.rst:23
msgid ""
"Coinages in both forms have been common in science fiction for at least "
"fifty years, and hackers (who are often SF fans) have probably been making "
"‘-oid’ jargon for almost that long [though GLS and I can personally confirm "
"only that they were already common in the mid-1970s —ESR]."
msgstr ""
"両方の形での造語は、少なくとも50年間SFで一般的であり、ハッカー(しばしばSFファンである)は、おそらくほぼそれと同じくらい長く‘-oid’のジャーゴンを作ってきた[もっとも、GLSと私が個人的に確認できるのは、1970年代半ばにはすでに一般的だったということだけだが——ESR]。"
